{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585969"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15043"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15043"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67566"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7731"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53018"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18887"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67566"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA urinary sediment examination reveals cylindrical structures containing degenerating renal tubular cells that appear dense and coarse under light microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this urinary cast type?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Granular cast","Hyaline cast","Waxy cast","Epithelial cast","Red blood cell cast"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description matches a \u003Cstrong\u003Egranular cast\u003C/strong\u003E, which forms when cellular material (usually from degraded renal tubular epithelial cells) breaks down within the cast matrix. These appear dark and coarse under microscopy due to the presence of cellular debris.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline casts\u003C/strong\u003E are clear, transparent and homogeneous in appearance, consisting mainly of Tamm-Horsfall protein\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaxy casts\u003C/strong\u003E have a dull, waxy appearance with sharp, often cracked edges and are typically seen in chronic kidney disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpithelial casts\u003C/strong\u003E contain intact renal tubular epithelial cells rather than degraded cellular material\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed blood cell casts\u003C/strong\u003E contain intact red blood cells and appear reddish-brown, indicating glomerular bleeding\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGranular casts are clinically significant as they typically indicate acute tubular injury or degeneration. The granules represent breakdown products of cells that have sloughed off the tubular epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Granular casts form when cellular material degrades within the tubular lumen, appearing dark and coarse under microscopy","Granular casts typically indicate acute tubular injury or cellular degeneration in the kidney","The appearance of urinary casts under microscopy provides diagnostic clues about underlying kidney pathology"],"references":["Dvanajscak Z, Cossey LN, Larsen CP. A practical approach to the pathology of renal intratubular casts. Semin Diagn Pathol. 2020 May;37(3):127-134. doi: 10.1053/j.semdp.2020.02.001. Epub 2020 Feb 14. PMID: 32147230.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53018"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15043"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53018"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:12:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:13:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7731"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67566"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt